          title: "What is a Derivative? The Foundational Concept",
          text: "A derivative is a financial contract whose value is 'derived' from an underlying asset — a stock, index, commodity, or currency. Derivatives do not have intrinsic value on their own; they are agreements between two parties about the future behavior of something else.\n\nThe two primary types are **Futures** (obligation to buy/sell at a fixed price on a future date) and **Options** (the *right* but not the *obligation* to buy/sell). Derivatives were invented not for speculation but for **hedging** — allowing farmers to lock in wheat prices before harvest, airlines to lock in jet fuel costs, and exporters to lock in USD exchange rates. The speculation use case came later and is what makes derivatives both fascinating and dangerous for retail participants.\n\nIn India, the NSE's F&O (Futures and Options) segment is the largest derivatives market in the world by volume. Daily, over ₹1,00,000 crore in notional value trades hands. SEBI studies show that 89% of retail F&O traders lose money over any 3-year period. Understanding why requires understanding the mechanics.",
          keyTakeaway: "Derivatives derive value from underlying assets. They were created for hedging, not gambling. 89% of retail participants lose money.",
          example: "An airline buys crude oil futures at $80/barrel 6 months before delivery. If oil rises to $100, the airline saved ₹20/barrel on thousands of barrels — that's hedging."
